references: The importance of our resource lies primarily in the fact that it fills a notable gap in the existing literature and libraries. In particular, Elliot (Anelli et al., 2021) and DaisyRec (Anelli et al., 2021) and DaisyRec (Sun et al., 2020) lack SRS models, while Cornac (Sun et al., 2020) lack SRS models, while Cornac (Salah et al., 2020) and RecPack (Salah et al., 2020) and RecPack (Michiels et al., 2022) provide only GRU4Rec among newer models. Although ReChorus (Michiels et al., 2022) provide only GRU4Rec among newer models. Although ReChorus (Wang et al., 2020) supports many models, it lacks one of the most cited ones (BERT4Rec) and modern ones. Conversely, RecBole (Wang et al., 2020) supports many models, it lacks one of the most cited ones (BERT4Rec) and modern ones. Conversely, RecBole (Zhao et al., 2021) stands out as a comprehensive framework that is widely used in the field. However, it requires the creation of a subclass of its classes to develop new models or datasets. In contrast, our approach allows the extension of the PyTorch standard class for all new models. Furthermore, existing literature highlights suboptimal performance metrics, timing, and implementation quality in RecBole (Zhao et al., 2021) stands out as a comprehensive framework that is widely used in the field. However, it requires the creation of a subclass of its classes to develop new models or datasets. In contrast, our approach allows the extension of the PyTorch standard class for all new models. Furthermore, existing literature highlights suboptimal performance metrics, timing, and implementation quality in RecBole (Hidasi and Czapp, 2023a; Petrov and Macdonald, 2022). Recbole’s performance, evaluated on the same number of epochs, is compromised by performing many iterations per epoch due to their data augmentation method (Hidasi and Czapp, 2023a; Petrov and Macdonald, 2022). Recbole’s performance, evaluated on the same number of epochs, is compromised by performing many iterations per epoch due to their data augmentation method 8 88 88https://recbole.io/docs/recbole/recbole.data.dataset.sequential_dataset.html. Moreover, they did not implement BCE loss, which is used in several works (Kang and McAuley, 2018), as also indicated on the official GitHub repository (Kang and McAuley, 2018), as also indicated on the official GitHub repository 9 99 99https://github.com/RUCAIBox/RecBole/issues/1667, so their implementations are not loyal to the originals. We changed their loss to be consistent with the original works. Table 2 shows the comparison between our implementation and that of RecBole using ML-1M and the three most common and widely used models in the literature: SASRec, GRU4Rec, and BERT4Rec, in terms of metrics and time. By RecBole a , we refer to models that are tracked until they reach our metrics, while by RecBole a, we refer to models that are tracked until they reach our metrics, while by RecBole b we refer to models that are tracked for our own time. The experimental setup is the same as described in b we refer to models that are tracked for our own time. The experimental setup is the same as described in Section 5. We outperform RecBole in every model.

references: In Table 3 we present the performance metrics of the reproduced models on the six datasets considered in this study. For the sake of experimental consistency, we maintain a uniform embedding size of 50 across all models. The input sequence lengths are set to 200 for FS-TKY, ML-20M, ML-1M, 100 for ML-100k and FS-NYC, and 50 for Beauty.

Interestingly, SASRec emerges as the best-performing model when using the largest embedding size, a finding not immediately apparent from Table 3. This highlights the nuanced relationship between model architecture, embedding size and performance.
